Now, were you involved at all in the setting up of 
the UTR and the T-Center, or did you take advantage

33:04.913 --> 33:12.703
of most of the center? You're talking about the 
Small Business Development Company Center,

33:12.883 --> 33:19.812
SBDC, Small Business Development Center. To the 
extent that I met with John Rouse up there and told

33:19.832 --> 33:23.957
him what we were doing here, and

33:25.675 --> 33:35.144
had some preliminary discussions with some of his 
people, offered our services. Occasionally he

33:35.865 --> 33:42.431
sends somebody down here to talk to us, and he 
thinks that they need our help more than his, and

33:35.865 --> 33:42.431
that sort of thing. And I send people up there when I 
think that they need his help more than ours. So

33:47.416 --> 33:50.839
from that standpoint, I was not directly involved 
in setting it up. Harry Whitmore, I guess, had

33:51.379 --> 33:53.001
handled that. Harry had skipped it in there. to the 
extent that there was a transfer of information,

33:55.240 --> 34:00.685
yeah, it wasn't local. Could he deal with

34:00.705 --> 34:06.991
inside the system? Inside the A&M system? Yeah. 
All right. Inside the A&M system, again, it's

34:10.454 --> 34:23.847
College of Business, TEAS, any other college dean 
that we need. Bill

34:24.738 --> 34:38.792
Mews, Mark Money, I

34:24.738 --> 34:38.792
guess indirectly through Perry Atkinson.

34:42.376 --> 34:49.783
I've had some dealings with agriculture with the 
Ag Experiment Station.

34:51.772 --> 34:52.633
Other than that, no. It's mostly business and 
engineering. Outside, too, by the way, the

34:57.477 --> 35:03.422
sources of capital, venture capitalists, that 
sort of commercial world. You do try and get them

35:03.442 --> 35:07.766
together with the capital. Yeah, when it's 
advisable. Once you've gotten past that stage.

35:10.788 --> 35:14.071
Yeah, right now, we don't have anything big enough 
to go to venture capital with. We've used local

35:16.333 --> 35:19.596
financing on that. But when you get up toward the 
million mark, and you really get your act put

35:21.792 --> 35:25.035
together, then you can go and watch a cat bus. But 
you have helped them get together with local

35:26.557 --> 35:28.759
planners? Yeah. What do you do as, you know, you've 
got whole organizations that I put, do you as

35:32.742 --> 35:41.771
director of this, of this invent, what stages do 
you get into? I don't know, inspire a lead, put out

35:41.791 --> 35:43.192
fires. I see my role as being the interface with the 
outside. and a policy role, and a supervisory role

35:52.235 --> 36:03.155
over procedures, and particularly the stage four 
programs. And for instance, right now I'm missing

36:04.297 --> 36:13.433
our Wednesday morning staff meeting, which is not 
a staff meeting per se, but it's a stage four review

36:04.297 --> 36:13.433
meeting. Now, what we do is when a program gets to 
this implementation stage where we're actually

36:14.105 --> 36:26.664
doing product development and actually running 
the business part and actually sending out market

36:14.105 --> 36:26.664
researchers, we appoint a faculty member as team 
leader. And he basically puts together a little

36:26.684 --> 36:29.088
company. He's got some marketing people, and he's 
got some finance people, and he's got some

36:29.869 --> 36:34.336
engineering people. He's got some strategy 
people. He may play several of these roles

36:36.519 --> 36:38.502
himself. But whatever he needs, we try to get for 
him in the way of talent. It's his job, then, to try

36:44.092 --> 36:58.875
to keep the thing on track, try to hit the schedule 
objectives, milestones, and bring the program

36:44.092 --> 36:58.875
in. So once a week, we spend a half hour per program 
in which he reports what's going on, what his

36:58.895 --> 37:08.269
problems are, what help he needs. And this meeting 
is just the team leader, the two associate

37:09.130 --> 37:12.816
directors, and myself. And we've set up a 
procedure where when the half hour is up, that's

37:14.315 --> 37:19.561
the end of that meter. If we have to meet more on 
that, we reschedule that particular month. This

37:25.409 --> 37:31.696
way, you don't wind up with some projects being 
cheated and others getting too much attention.

37:34.760 --> 37:38.725
I meet with the inventors frequently. And I like to 
get involved myself with them. Oh, particularly

37:42.682 --> 37:46.087
ones in which I feel particularly competent. 
Power generation, thermodynamics, things that I

37:46.748 --> 37:53.939
may have been involved in in the past. In industry, 
I think I'm going to bring some insight in on these

37:53.959 --> 37:57.925
things. So I like to get my hands dirty on those.

38:03.553 --> 38:06.698
But to come up with a job description, that's 
difficult. I think it's difficult in the whole

38:07.437 --> 38:09.380
organization. Yeah, it really is. I think if you 
can't, that's why they have such nice titles. You

38:13.026 --> 38:14.648
know, you're vice president of sales. Everybody 
knows what that is, so you don't have to explain it

38:14.708 --> 38:18.755
to them. But I guess, you know, to the extent that 
I'm the president of the company here, reporting

38:19.376 --> 38:28.650
to my board of directors, and fairly autonomous. 
So from that standpoint, it's very satisfying.

38:31.895 --> 38:34.659
And I've been satisfied with the results. A little 
anxious that they We stopped popping things out

38:36.547 --> 38:42.813
faster, but it just took longer to get them through 
the pipeline than I thought they would. In terms of

38:43.294 --> 38:53.264
flexibility, are you as flexible

38:43.294 --> 38:53.264
here as you were in the private sector? Yes and no. I 
think that,

38:53.904 --> 38:59.029
well, let's put it this way. It's harder to do 
things. You don't have as much money available.

39:07.934 --> 39:17.304
Because people are locked into semester 
schedules that are scheduled a year and a half in

39:07.934 --> 39:17.304
advance, they're not always available. And in a 
company, it was always possible to get ahold of

39:18.765 --> 39:22.790
somebody for some length of time.

39:26.634 --> 39:29.857
I remember talking to one of my former Continental 
Group associates. And he said, what kind of

39:31.078 --> 39:33.581
funding do you have for this operation? I said, 
well, we've got a million dollars for the

39:33.601 --> 39:35.903
biennium. So that's a half million dollars a year. 
They said, Frank, that used to be your expense

39:37.837 --> 39:40.680
account.

39:45.064 --> 39:59.679
So from the standpoint of money, in the standpoint 
of being able to go outside and get help, we try very

39:45.064 --> 39:59.679
hard to use the help internally. As a result, it 
slows things down. Recently, we did have to go

40:01.721 --> 40:03.443
outside. And gee, just the procedures of getting 
an outside consultant, I get with the governor,

40:06.642 --> 40:09.765
they're okay.

40:13.269 --> 40:13.429
Amazing. I guess approval levels, yeah, there's 
also approval. We had a letter come through here

40:15.671 --> 40:32.008
the other day requesting

40:15.671 --> 40:32.008
permission for, well, AINVENT was going to fund 
the presentation of a paper in France, and this was

40:15.671 --> 40:32.008
because of some work that had been done.

40:33.710 --> 40:37.415
it turned out that it looked like it required 19 
approvals. You know, it started out with the guy

40:37.535 --> 40:54.717
requesting it, went through his assistant 
department head, his department head, went

40:37.535 --> 40:54.717
through his assistant dean, his dean, came over to 
T's, went through Skip, went through me, then was

40:37.535 --> 40:54.717
going to head on up through Vanderveer and Hanson, 
and ultimately, I don't know, through two state

40:37.535 --> 40:54.717
senators and the governor or something. I 
couldn't believe it.

41:02.246 --> 41:02.687
Do you... Well,

41:04.000 --> 41:33.501
again, I believe that any time that you can inject 
the outside world into the university

41:04.000 --> 41:33.501
environment, that you're doing everybody a 
favor. To

41:34.696 --> 42:00.265
some extent, I guess I was a little bit taken aback 
the first time I started working with the faculty,

41:34.696 --> 42:00.265
and it sort of reminded me of being out in business 
and having a brand new, eager, intelligent,

41:34.696 --> 42:00.265
hardworking MBA who is just chock full of theory, 
and doesn't even know who to call to get the right

42:01.325 --> 42:06.633
answer to something. I think that the standpoint 
that they're able to say, oh, yeah, well, I talked

42:06.653 --> 42:20.253
to 50 guys in the oil business

42:06.653 --> 42:20.253
and I think we ought to go back and hit this guy and 
that guy and this guy because they seem to know more

42:06.653 --> 42:20.253
about it. That sort of thing I think is useful. I 
think we're doing the university a fantastic

42:22.776 --> 42:29.526
service in what we're doing with the graduate 
students. We've got an MBA candidate now, first

42:30.350 --> 42:35.838
year MBA candidate, that's going to start a 
business. Not of her own, but she's doing a foreign

42:35.858 --> 42:41.446
event, getting something else started here. And I 
think that's just a marvelous experience. And

42:45.432 --> 42:55.846
what it's doing is showing them that it's not an 
impossibly difficult thing to do, and it's

42:45.432 --> 42:55.846
something they can handle. And we use graduate 
students on two bases. is the research assistant

43:00.472 --> 43:05.197
program, we just hire them. And the other is the 
intern program. And the intern program is for

43:08.660 --> 43:15.007
second year MBA students with an engineering 
undergraduate degree. And we give them three

43:16.428 --> 43:19.992
hours of credit in exchange for 10 hours a week. On 
the other hand, we will not make the same work

43:20.873 --> 43:28.861
demands that we would make of a research 
assistant. And we leave them pretty much set their

43:30.560 --> 43:49.280
own program, follow their own nose, and to try to 
absorb as much as possible about what we're doing

43:30.560 --> 43:49.280
and how we do it and how people react and that sort of 
thing.

43:50.462 --> 43:54.867
Also, they've got a right to sit in on anything they 
want to. They don't have to necessarily be

43:57.650 --> 43:59.892
assigned to it. I'd go on a trip and investigate 
another project, and we'd be fine. It's all part of

44:05.099 --> 44:07.221
the deal. That's for credit towards their degree. 
Yeah. So from that standpoint, I think that we're

44:11.606 --> 44:16.310
benefiting the university. I think eventually 
we'll do with money.

44:21.976 --> 44:24.438
Have you... Oh, there's another thing, too. A lot 
of things that, again, no matter how good an

44:24.458 --> 44:29.743
invention is, somebody's got to want to push it. 
and wear that force here. Now I have been

44:34.222 --> 44:39.387
disappointed in the number, a small number of 
university inventions we've seen. Most of our

44:40.188 --> 44:43.772
inventions come from outside or coming from 
students. And faculty members for some reason are

44:43.792 --> 44:51.460
not bringing them forward.

44:51.480 --> 44:52.941
Possibly. Possibly. I think also that Some of them 
are so esoteric that there may not be any

44:55.373 --> 45:00.240
commercial application. If

45:00.421 --> 45:07.691
you started a business and sold the world market, 
you'd sell three windows. That would be it. At a

45:10.476 --> 45:15.543
high price point.

45:16.244 --> 45:16.705
Yeah. Have you consciously made any changes in the 
direction that is going? Well,

45:25.462 --> 45:34.775
yeah, I think we sort of came full circle on the 
relative roles of graduate students and faculty.

45:34.795 --> 45:47.352
I originally started out thinking that the MBA 
candidates were going to be the most useful

45:34.795 --> 45:47.352
workers, mainly because they were aimed toward 
the commercial world and their objectives would

45:34.795 --> 45:47.352
be the same as inventors.

